{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3327414,"name":"","username":"mjjain","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/7cd45c/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-08T01:03:27.156Z","cooked":"<p>Hey, I have a quick question. I am trying to run a command in parallel with a path following command. In my AutoIntakeNote command, i’m using an optical sensor to detect if a note has been picked up, and when it has, I’m telling the collector to retract back in and feed the note to our pivoting shooter. The problem is that if I place the note way closer to the robot (way before the path finishes), it seems that the path following the command ends instantly.</p>
<p>However, the command scheduler does indeed schedule the command i’m passing in, and note is still fed to the shooter as expected, i just want the path following command to not be interrupted as well. I suspect the .schedule() method is canceling all other current commands, even though it says, " Does nothing for commands already scheduled." Any ideas on how to fix this?</p>
<p>Execute method of my AutoIntakeNoteCmd:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">@Override
  public void execute() {

    if (collector.isNotePresent()) {

      CommandScheduler.getInstance()
          .schedule(new SequentialCommandGroup(new ParallelCommandGroup(new TiltShooterToCollectorCmd(shooter),
              new TiltCollectorToShooterCmd(collector)), new WaitCommand(0.5),
              new ShooterAndCollectorIndexerCmd(collector, shooter)));

    } else {
      collector.setRollerMotor(0.55);
    }

  }
</code></pre>
<p><div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/8/d/8dbdaf55e6649e3a34fb305b863f7524161ee58d.png" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/8dbdaf55e6649e3a34fb305b863f7524161ee58d" title="image"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/8/d/8dbdaf55e6649e3a34fb305b863f7524161ee58d_2_690x326.png" alt="image" data-base62-sha1="kdTIIVVliGuUiqkDLvEtiMnYC5L" width="690" height="326" srcset="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/8/d/8dbdaf55e6649e3a34fb305b863f7524161ee58d_2_690x326.png, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/8/d/8dbdaf55e6649e3a34fb305b863f7524161ee58d.png 1.5x, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/8/d/8dbdaf55e6649e3a34fb305b863f7524161ee58d.png 2x" data-dominant-color="2F3555"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">image</span><span class="informations">942×446 21.5 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div><br>
<div class="lightbox-wrapper"><a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/1/f/1f9f66f355286803ccdba1fe1b88beca4f870102.png" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/1f9f66f355286803ccdba1fe1b88beca4f870102" title="image"><img src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/1/f/1f9f66f355286803ccdba1fe1b88beca4f870102_2_690x200.png" alt="image" data-base62-sha1="4vKjMGkwH6cpD1yybifthCRsjlM" width="690" height="200" srcset="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/1/f/1f9f66f355286803ccdba1fe1b88beca4f870102_2_690x200.png, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/optimized/3X/1/f/1f9f66f355286803ccdba1fe1b88beca4f870102_2_1035x300.png 1.5x, https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/1/f/1f9f66f355286803ccdba1fe1b88beca4f870102.png 2x" data-dominant-color="232424"><div class="meta"><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#far-image"></use></svg><span class="filename">image</span><span class="informations">1350×392 38.8 KB</span><svg class="fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon" aria-hidden="true"><use href="#discourse-expand"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":19,"updated_at":"2024-03-08T01:04:02.394Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":139,"reads":98,"readers_count":97,"score":719.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":457807,"topic_slug":"commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/8/d/8dbdaf55e6649e3a34fb305b863f7524161ee58d.png","internal":true,"reflection":false,"clicks":0},{"url":"https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/1/f/1f9f66f355286803ccdba1fe1b88beca4f870102.png","internal":true,"reflection":false,"clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":51252,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel/457807/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true,"can_vote":false},{"id":3327420,"name":"Peter Johnson","username":"Peter_Johnson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/peter_johnson/{size}/10417_2.png","created_at":"2024-03-08T01:07:49.367Z","cooked":"<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="mjjain" data-post="1" data-topic="457807">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/7cd45c/48.png" class="avatar"> mjjain:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>I suspect the .schedule() method is canceling all other current commands, even though it says, " Does nothing for commands already scheduled."</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>It will cancel all commands which use overlapping subsystems to the command being scheduled.  This is a core tenet of the command framework (you can’t have two commands that require the same subsystem running at the same time).</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":19,"updated_at":"2024-03-08T01:07:49.367Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":81,"readers_count":80,"score":41.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":457807,"topic_slug":"commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel","display_username":"Peter Johnson","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":13575,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Volunteer WPILib Developer, CSA"},"post_url":"/t/commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel/457807/2","custom_user_title":"Volunteer WPILib Developer, CSA","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3327424,"name":"","username":"mjjain","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/7cd45c/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-08T01:09:55.540Z","cooked":"<p>That makes sense, but the interesting thing is that I removed the addRequirements line in the constructor of my command as a sanity check, and the same thing still happened. Even with it uncommented, the command only requires the shooter and collector subsystems and not the drivetrain. The follow path command only requires the drivetrain, so there don’t seem to be any conflicting subsystem requirements unless I’m missing something.</p>
<p>Pretty sure this is what pathplanner is doing:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">/**
   * Builds a command to follow a path. PathPlannerLib commands will also trigger event markers
   * along the way.
   *
   * @param path the path to follow
   * @return a path following command with for the given path
   * @throws AutoBuilderException if the AutoBuilder has not been configured
   */
  public static Command followPath(PathPlannerPath path) {
    if (!isConfigured()) {
      throw new AutoBuilderException(
          "Auto builder was used to build a path following command before being configured");
    }

    return pathFollowingCommandBuilder.apply(path);
  }
</code></pre>
<p>And in my SwerveBase AutoBuilder code:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto"> // Configure the AutoBuilder last
    AutoBuilder.configureHolonomic(
        this::getPose, // Robot pose supplier
        this::resetOdometry, // Method to reset odometry (will be called if your auto has a starting pose)
        this::getRobotRelativeSpeeds, // ChassisSpeeds supplier. MUST BE ROBOT RELATIVE
        this::driveFieldRelative, // Method that will drive the robot given ROBOT RELATIVE ChassisSpeeds
        new HolonomicPathFollowerConfig( // HolonomicPathFollowerConfig, this should likely live in your Constants class
            new PIDConstants(SwerveBaseConstants.translationkP, 0.0, 0.0), // Translation PID constants
            new PIDConstants(SwerveBaseConstants.rotationkP, 0.0, 0.0), // Rotation PID constants
            SwerveBaseConstants.maxSpeed, // Max module speed, in m/s
            SwerveBaseConstants.driveBaseRadius, // Drive base radius in meters. Distance from robot center to furthest
                                                 // module.
            new ReplanningConfig() // Default path replanning config. See the API for the options here
        ),
        () -&gt; {
          // Boolean supplier that controls when the path will be mirrored for the red
          // alliance
          // This will flip the path being followed to the red side of the field.
          // THE ORIGIN WILL REMAIN ON THE BLUE SIDE

          var alliance = DriverStation.getAlliance();
          if (alliance.isPresent()) {
            return alliance.get() == DriverStation.Alliance.Red;
          }
          return false;
        },
        this);
</code></pre>
<p>I’m passing the SwerveBase as a requirement with the <em>this</em> keyword.</p>
<p>So I can see what you were saying about how the .schedule() method handles requirement conflicts, but the subsystem requirements shouldn’t conflict because the drivetrain is never added as a requirement in the AutoIntakeNoteCmd, and the collector and shooter are never accessed in AutoBuilder.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto"> /**
   * Schedules a command for execution. Does nothing if the command is already scheduled. If a
   * command's requirements are not available, it will only be started if all the commands currently
   * using those requirements have been scheduled as interruptible. If this is the case, they will
   * be interrupted and the command will be scheduled.
   *
   * @param command the command to schedule. If null, no-op.
   */
  private void schedule(Command command) {
    if (command == null) {
      DriverStation.reportWarning("Tried to schedule a null command", true);
      return;
    }
    if (m_inRunLoop) {
      m_toSchedule.add(command);
      return;
    }

    requireNotComposed(command);

    // Do nothing if the scheduler is disabled, the robot is disabled and the command doesn't
    // run when disabled, or the command is already scheduled.
    if (m_disabled
        || isScheduled(command)
        || RobotState.isDisabled() &amp;&amp; !command.runsWhenDisabled()) {
      return;
    }

    Set&lt;Subsystem&gt; requirements = command.getRequirements();

    // Schedule the command if the requirements are not currently in-use.
    if (Collections.disjoint(m_requirements.keySet(), requirements)) {
      initCommand(command, requirements);
    } else {
      // Else check if the requirements that are in use have all have interruptible commands,
      // and if so, interrupt those commands and schedule the new command.
      for (Subsystem requirement : requirements) {
        Command requiring = requiring(requirement);
        if (requiring != null
            &amp;&amp; requiring.getInterruptionBehavior() == InterruptionBehavior.kCancelIncoming) {
          return;
        }
      }
      for (Subsystem requirement : requirements) {
        Command requiring = requiring(requirement);
        if (requiring != null) {
          cancel(requiring, Optional.of(command));
        }
      }
      initCommand(command, requirements);
    }
  }
</code></pre>
<p>Is there a different way to do this or am I making a silly mistake somewhere?</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":19,"updated_at":"2024-03-08T01:26:44.823Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":5,"reads":79,"readers_count":78,"score":40.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":457807,"topic_slug":"commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":5,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":13575,"username":"Peter_Johnson","name":"Peter Johnson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/peter_johnson/{size}/10417_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":51252,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel/457807/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3327563,"name":"","username":"mjjain","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/7cd45c/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-08T04:01:14.518Z","cooked":"<p>Do you have any ideas based on my reply ? Any help is appreciated, thank you again!</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":19,"updated_at":"2024-03-08T04:01:14.518Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":48,"readers_count":47,"score":9.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":457807,"topic_slug":"commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":13575,"username":"Peter_Johnson","name":"Peter Johnson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/peter_johnson/{size}/10417_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":51252,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel/457807/4","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3327686,"name":"NewtonCrosby","username":"NewtonCrosby","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/ed8c4c/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-08T12:32:16.571Z","cooked":"<p>So my quick readthrough of your logic is you want:</p>
<ol>
<li>Start intake</li>
<li>Run Intake until you detect note</li>
<li>In parallel, tilt collector and shooter toward each other</li>
<li>Wait a bit</li>
<li>Index note and shoot</li>
</ol>
<p>Psuedo code-ish:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">IntakeCommand(m_intake).until(m_intake::hasNote)
.andThen( ParallelCommand(TiltCollector, TiltShooter)
.andThen( WaitCommand(.5)
.andThen( ShooterAndCollectorIndexerCmd(collector, shooter)
</code></pre>
<p>Or something like that.</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":19,"updated_at":"2024-03-08T12:32:53.409Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":47,"readers_count":46,"score":14.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":457807,"topic_slug":"commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel","display_username":"NewtonCrosby","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":31346,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel/457807/5","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3327691,"name":"","username":"mjjain","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/7cd45c/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-08T12:41:35.803Z","cooked":"<p>Yeah, that seems to basically be what I’m doing, but how do I make it not end the path following command?</p>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":19,"updated_at":"2024-03-08T12:41:35.803Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":43,"readers_count":42,"score":18.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":457807,"topic_slug":"commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":31346,"username":"NewtonCrosby","name":"NewtonCrosby","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/ed8c4c/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":51252,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel/457807/6","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3327701,"name":"NewtonCrosby","username":"NewtonCrosby","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/ed8c4c/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-08T12:56:30.872Z","cooked":"<p>You are <em>basically</em> doing that…but not doing that.  What I’m suggesting, is the way you’ve contructed things is unnecessary, and there’s likely a cleaner way to do it.</p>
<p>If you composed and scheduled your intake command the way that I wrote it, you’d have no need to be calling <em>.schedule()</em> on anything, if indeed that is the root of the issue.</p>
<p>If your hope is to complete the sequence in the five steps I enumerated, there’s no need to shedule a new command at all.  You just need to build your command sequence similar to what I’ve done and it will work.</p>
<p>If for some reason you think you need to schedule a command at runtime, or you need to fork off a set of commands from your current command group (thus having a separate set of requirements etc) then you probably will need a <strong>DeferredCommand</strong> or a <strong>ProxyCommand</strong> in your current setup.</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":1,"posts_count":19,"updated_at":"2024-03-08T12:56:30.872Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":6,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":44,"readers_count":43,"score":18.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":457807,"topic_slug":"commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel","display_username":"NewtonCrosby","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":51252,"username":"mjjain","name":"","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/7cd45c/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":31346,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/commandscheduler-getinstance-schedule-seems-to-be-cancelling-with-path-following-command-in-parallel/457807/7","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3327703,"name":"Fletch","username":"Fletch1373","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png","created_at":"2024-03-08T12:58:02.505Z","cooked":"<p>Nothing about the code you shared seems to be requiring your drivetrain (or w